<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?><listPerson xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><person xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="CHR02" sex="1"><persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><roleName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/><forename xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Thomas</forename><surname xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Christie</surname><addName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/></persName><birth xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1761-10"><placeName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"> </placeName></birth><death xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1796-10"/><occupation xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">political writer</occupation><occupation xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/><note xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="editorial"><p xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Thomas Christie (1761-96), political writer (and merchant) who married Rebecca Thomson in 1792, who 
  was good friends with <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="WOL01">Wollstonecraft</persName>.
  The early refs, 1795-6 are attributed to Christie due to the context of <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="KIN01">King</persName>, <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="NEW01">Newton</persName>, 
    and <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="WOL01">Wollstonecraft/Imlay</persName>.  Godwin also read a text by him at this time
  possibly his contribution to the Revolution Controversy, <title xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Letters on the Revolution in France and the New Constitution</title>.
  There is also a <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="CHR03">Mrs Christie</persName> who appears 17 times, 1796-1802 and several times in conjunction
  with Wollstonecraft.</p><p xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">The final reference in Feb 1821 'Duel, John Scott and Christie' and refers to Jonathan Henry Christie,
  London agent for <title xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Blackwood</title>'s editor Lockhart.  See also the 'Public Events' file.</p><p xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">The penultimate ref, 20.5.1808, 'Christie's, w. MJ (sir Thos More and c.)'  refers to the auctioneer <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="CHR04">James 
  Christie</persName> (1773-1831), or at least to his premises. An advert in the <title xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Morning Chronicle</title> the previous day 
  advertises a sale of pictures assembled in the c17 by William Lenthal (d. 1662), speaker of the Long 
  Parliament, including 'the very celebrated Chef d'ouvre of Holbein, the Chancellor, Sir Thomas Moor and
  his family'. The sale was on Saturday 21st and the pictures 'may be viewed five days preceding the sale,
  and Catalogues had'.</p><p xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"> This leaves fifteen intervening Christies, from 1799 to 1803 (not including Mrs Christies). Of these, 11 are
  E Christie, 2 plain Christie, one Mr Christie and one R Christie. All remain uncoded.</p></note><bibl xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="other"><title xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">DNB</title></bibl><bibl xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="journalism"><title xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Morning Chronicle</title>, 19 May 1808</bibl><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="appearancesInDiary"><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1788"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1789"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1790"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1791"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1792"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1793"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1794"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1795"><date xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1795-03-22" n="notVenue" type="ah"/><date xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1795-12-30" n="notVenue" type="ah"/></ab><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1796"><date xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1796-04-15" n="notVenue" type="ah"/><date xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1796-04-23" n="notVenue" type="ah"/></ab><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1797"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1798"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1799"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1800"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1801"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1802"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1803"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1804"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1805"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1806"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1807"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1808"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1809"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1810"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1811"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.